At my most insecure, I was my most passionate. It was when I didn’t know who I was that I was most certain that I could be anything. I don’t think I ever questioned whether I was smart enough to go to college. I knew I could do it. I knew I was going to go to college. I didn’t know what I was going to study. I didn’t know where I was going to go to college. I didn’t know what I wanted to do. But I knew I was going to do it. I was a product of a privileged family. My parents had done all the right things and had all the right resources. They were proud of me and of my achievements. They encouraged me to go to the best college that I could. I had no doubts. Then I got into Harvard. It was one of the proudest moments of my life. I had accomplished what I had set out to do. Then, my dad asked me what I was going to study. I didn’t have an answer. He asked me what I was going to do with my life. I didn’t have an answer. He asked me if I knew what I wanted to do. I didn’t have an answer. Then he said something that really hurt. He said that he was really proud of me for getting into Harvard, but he didn’t think that I should go. He said that he wanted me to go to the school that I wanted to go to. He said that he didn’t think that I should go to Harvard if I didn’t know what I wanted to do. I was in shock. I couldn’t believe that my father, the one person who I had thought would never, ever doubt me, was now doubting me. I had no idea what I wanted to do with my life. But I knew that
